Here=E2=80=99s an unscripted plot twist: Netflix has become a villain in it=
s own documentary film, about a fertility specialist who secretly inseminat=
ed his patients, after disclosing the names of the doctor=E2=80=99s childre=
n without their consent. A lawsuit, now headed to a jury trial, raises the =
provocative question: Did they have a constitutional right to remain privat=
e?

ERIQ GARDNER ( https://puck.news/author/eriq-gardner/ )
ERIQ GARDNER ( https://puck.news/author/eriq-gardner/ )

Netflix, which has become a magnet for boundary-pushing lawsuits, is starin=
g down the barrel of yet another First Amendment trial. This one is related=
 to its chilling 2022 documentary Our Father, a Blumhouse production about =
Dr. Donald Cline, the Indiana fertility specialist who was revealed in 2015=
 to have secretly fathered at least 94 children by inseminating his unwitti=
ng patients. Netflix aggressively marketed the film, buying a Times Square =
billboard that featured Cline=E2=80=99s image and the teaser, =E2=80=9CCoul=
d he be your father?=E2=80=9D When the documentary catapulted to the top of=
 Netflix=E2=80=99s most watched list, Blumhouse=E2=80=99s Jason Blum tweete=
d, =E2=80=9CYea baby. That=E2=80=99s our movie!!! Number 1!=E2=80=9D

But not all of Cline=E2=80=99s biological children were thrilled about the =
documentary. Eight of the 94 kids participated in
interviews, and others provided personal photos, but two went in another di=
rection. Disturbed that a 23andMe genealogy chart showcased in the film rev=
ealed their identities, Sarah Bowling and Lori Kennard instead filed a laws=
uit. Through their attorney, Robert MacGill, they argued that the documenta=
ry, under the guise of exploring issues of consent and choice, had deprived=
 them of the very personal choice of disclosing their lineage.

The complexities of the case led U.S. District Judge Tanya Pratt to call fo=
r a trial. Off the bat, however, she dismissed a third plaintiff who had un=
dermined her privacy argument by attempting to share her story on actress K=
ate Hudson=E2=80=99s podcast. Pratt also dismissed claims that weren=E2=80=
=99t tied to privacy rights=E2=80=94including the emotional harm Bowling an=
d Kennard alleged they suffered from being associated with a =E2=80=9Cdespi=
cable=E2=80=9D film with =E2=80=9Cblasphemous=E2=80=9D scenes. (The movie o=
pens with a crucifix
looming next to the phrase =E2=80=9CBe fruitful and multiply=E2=80=9D befor=
e revealing an unsettling reenactment of an actor portraying Cline in an ac=
t of self-pleasure.) Instead, for Pratt, the key issue at hand is whether N=
etflix and Blumhouse had a constitutional right to disclose the identities =
of Bowling and Kennard in the manner that they did. So she threw the questi=
on to a jury.

The legal battleground here is the tort known as =E2=80=9Cpublic disclosure=
 of private facts=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a claim with a rich legal lineage spanni=
ng everything from a pap tailing Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis in the 1970s to=
 ESPN reporter Adam Schefter tweeting about an NFL star=E2=80=99s accidenta=
l finger loss at a July Fourth party to whether bots can reveal the flight =
paths of private jets carrying Elon Musk and Taylor Swift. Most infamously,=
 it was the same =E2=80=9Cpublic disclosure of private facts=E2=80=9D tort =
that brought down Gawker, after the site published snippets of a Hulk Hogan=
 sex
tape. While defamation cases often steal the limelight, this lesser-known l=
egal tactic is just as powerful.

Of course, every case has its nuances. For instance, it=E2=80=99s debatable=
 whether the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 ties to Dr. Cline constituted a genuinely =
private fact. (If the biological children were active on 23andMe or communi=
cated with each other in a Facebook group, was their family tree really con=
cealed?) Netflix=E2=80=99s counsel from Barnes & Thornburg delved deep into=
 the particulars of DNA submissions and digital footprints, prompting Judge=
 Pratt to conclude that limited disclosures, such as the identities of half=
-siblings, don=E2=80=99t fully strip away the veil of privacy. Nevertheless=
, Netflix managed to highlight Facebook posts, and the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 =
attendance at podcast events, as a form of self-publicity. The question for=
 the jury will be whether Bowling and Kennard maintained discretion over th=
eir identities as Cline=E2=80=99s offspring.

Bowling and Kennard
are each demanding compensatory damages of $1 per viewer. Leveraging Netfli=
x=E2=80=99s viewership data=E2=80=94about 15 million people watched Our Fat=
her, from beginning to end, before a revised version blurred their names=E2=
=80=94that comes out to $14.7 million for Kennard and $18 million for Bowli=
ng, according to their expert witness. Pratt is also allowing punitive dama=
ges=E2=80=94which, if Netflix loses, could amplify the verdict tenfold or m=
ore. (The Indiana jury is sure to get an earful about Netflix=E2=80=99s dee=
p pockets.) The trial is scheduled to begin December 2. The streamer has be=
en granted a request that the jury watch the documentary in its entirety.

