_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

It=E2=80=99s All a Blur=E2=80=A6

Questions remain regarding the documentary=E2=80=99s handling of sensitive =
information. Did Netflix act recklessly? Was there a higher public interest=
 at stake that warranted such disclosure? This is where things get peculiar=
: The filmmakers knew that some of the offspring cherished their privacy an=
d obtained signed releases from participants. Assurances were made to omit =
personal information without consent, and some names were indeed blurred. Y=
et Bowling and Kennard=E2=80=99s names were exposed. How?

It appears they simply fell through the cracks=E2=80=94although it=E2=80=99=
s unclear if Alonzo Wickers, the lawyer Blumhouse hired to conduct a pre-re=
lease review, and who gave notes on the documentary, actually viewed the ve=
rsion that displayed the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 names before it streamed. Netf=
lix may have broadcast an unapproved cut, as evidenced by
sealed records. When alerted that an uncleared name had been broadcast, a N=
etflix employee=E2=80=99s reaction =E2=80=94=E2=80=9COMG. LOL.=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94led the judge to open the door to punitive damages. (Be careful what =
you say on Slack, kids!)

Wickers, due to testify at the coming trial, doesn=E2=80=99t believe Blumho=
use had a legal requirement to blur the names. And Netflix is leaning hard =
on First Amendment principles. =E2=80=9CIndividuals, documentary filmmakers=
, and the press have the right to tell a story of public interest even when=
 it sweeps in otherwise private information of third parties,=E2=80=9D its =
lawyers argue.

Despite arguments that the inclusion of names added to the film=E2=80=99s c=
redibility and authenticity, Judge Pratt was dismissive. Then again, she ha=
sn=E2=80=99t barred Netflix from drawing the bigger picture for jurors. Wit=
h a lot of money on the line, I anticipate Netflix will contest the notion =
that it should be financially penalized for a fleeting glimpse of footage t=
hat perhaps no
one paused to scrutinize. Netflix may also push a counter-narrative about t=
he need to shield speech against opportunistic litigation. A sordid and sad=
 tale of a deeply disturbed fertility doctor isn=E2=80=99t the only legacy =
these jurors will inherit. They=E2=80=99ll be grappling with the constituti=
onal DNA in our legal code that=E2=80=99s designed to safeguard free expres=
sion, too.

Thanks, Eriq. That=E2=80=99s all for today, see you Thursday.

Matt

