          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Netflix, which has =
become a magnet for boundary-pushing lawsuits, is staring down the barrel o=
f yet <i>another</i> First Amendment trial. This one is related to its chil=
ling 2022 documentary <i>Our Father</i>, a Blumhouse production about Dr. <=
b>Donald Cline</b>, the Indiana fertility specialist who was revealed in 20=
15 to have secretly fathered at least <i>94 children</i> by inseminating hi=
s unwitting patients. Netflix aggressively marketed the film, buying a Time=
s Square billboard that featured Cline=E2=80=99s image and the teaser, =E2=
=80=9CCould he be your father?=E2=80=9D When the documentary catapulted to =
the top of Netflix=E2=80=99s most watched list, Blumhouse=E2=80=99s <b>Jaso=
n Blum</b> tweeted, =E2=80=9CYea baby. That=E2=80=99s our movie!!! Number 1=
!=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>But not all of Cline=E2=80=99s biological children wer=
e thrilled about the documentary. Eight of the 94 kids participated in
interviews, and others provided personal photos, but two went in another di=
rection. Disturbed that a 23andMe genealogy chart showcased in the film rev=
ealed their identities, <b>Sarah Bowling</b> and <b>Lori Kennard</b> instea=
d filed a lawsuit. Through their attorney, <b>Robert MacGill</b>, they argu=
ed that the documentary, under the guise of exploring issues of consent and=
 choice, had deprived them of the very personal choice of disclosing their =
lineage.<br/><br/>The complexities of the case led U.S. District Judge <b>T=
anya Pratt</b> to call for a trial. Off the bat, however, she dismissed a t=
hird plaintiff who had undermined her privacy argument by attempting to sha=
re her story on actress <b>Kate Hudson</b>=E2=80=99s podcast. Pratt also di=
smissed claims that weren=E2=80=99t tied to privacy rights=E2=80=94includin=
g the emotional harm Bowling and Kennard alleged they suffered from being a=
ssociated with a =E2=80=9Cdespicable=E2=80=9D film with =E2=80=9Cblasphemou=
s=E2=80=9D scenes. (The movie opens with a crucifix
looming next to the phrase =E2=80=9CBe fruitful and multiply=E2=80=9D befor=
e revealing an unsettling reenactment of an actor portraying Cline in an ac=
t of self-pleasure.) Instead, for Pratt, the key issue at hand is whether N=
etflix and Blumhouse had a constitutional right to disclose the identities =
of Bowling and Kennard in the manner that they did. So she threw the questi=
on to a jury.<br/><br/>The legal battleground here is the tort known as =E2=
=80=9Cpublic disclosure of private facts=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a claim with a ri=
ch legal lineage spanning everything from a pap tailing <b>Jacqueline Kenne=
dy Onassis</b> in the 1970s to ESPN reporter <b>Adam Schefter</b> tweeting =
about an NFL star=E2=80=99s accidental finger loss at a July Fourth party t=
o whether bots can reveal the flight paths of private jets carrying <b>Elon=
 Musk</b> and <b>Taylor Swift</b>. Most infamously, it was the same =E2=80=
=9Cpublic disclosure of private facts=E2=80=9D tort that brought down Gawke=
r, after the site published snippets of a <b>Hulk Hogan</b> sex
tape. While defamation cases often steal the limelight, this lesser-known l=
egal tactic is just as powerful. <br/><br/>Of course, every case has its nu=
ances. For instance, it=E2=80=99s debatable whether the plaintiffs=E2=80=99=
 ties to Dr. Cline constituted a genuinely <i>private</i> fact. (If the bio=
logical children were active on 23andMe or communicated with each other in =
a Facebook group, was their family tree really concealed?) Netflix=E2=80=99=
s counsel from Barnes &amp; Thornburg delved deep into the particulars of D=
NA submissions and digital footprints, prompting Judge Pratt to conclude th=
at limited disclosures, such as the identities of half-siblings, don=E2=80=
=99t fully strip away the veil of privacy. Nevertheless, Netflix managed to=
 highlight Facebook posts, and the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 attendance at podcas=
t events, as a form of self-publicity. The question for the jury will be wh=
ether Bowling and Kennard maintained discretion over their identities as Cl=
ine=E2=80=99s offspring.<br/><br/>Bowling and Kennard
are each demanding compensatory damages of  $1 <i>per</i> viewer. Leveragin=
g Netflix=E2=80=99s viewership data=E2=80=94about 15 million people watched=
 <i>Our Father</i>, from beginning to end, before a revised version blurred=
 their names=E2=80=94that comes out to $14.7 million for Kennard and $18 mi=
llion for Bowling, according to their expert witness. Pratt is also allowin=
g punitive damages=E2=80=94which, if Netflix loses, could amplify the verdi=
ct tenfold or more. (The Indiana jury is sure to get an earful about Netfli=
x=E2=80=99s deep pockets.) The trial is scheduled to begin December 2. The =
streamer has been granted a request that the jury watch the documentary in =
its entirety. <br/></td>
