         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s11">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Questions remain re=
garding the documentary=E2=80=99s handling of sensitive information. Did Ne=
tflix act recklessly? Was there a higher public interest at stake that warr=
anted such disclosure? This is where things get peculiar: The filmmakers <i=
>knew</i> that some of the offspring cherished their privacy and obtained s=
igned releases from participants. Assurances were made to omit personal inf=
ormation without consent, and some names were indeed blurred. Yet Bowling a=
nd Kennard=E2=80=99s names were exposed. How? <br/><br/>It appears they sim=
ply fell through the cracks=E2=80=94although it=E2=80=99s unclear if <b>Alo=
nzo Wickers</b>, the lawyer Blumhouse hired to conduct a pre-release review=
, and who gave notes on the documentary, actually viewed the version that d=
isplayed the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 names before it streamed. Netflix may have=
 broadcast an unapproved cut, as evidenced by
sealed records. When alerted that an uncleared name had been broadcast, a N=
etflix employee=E2=80=99s reaction =E2=80=94=E2=80=9COMG. LOL.=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94led the judge to open the door to punitive damages. (Be careful what =
you say on Slack, kids!)<br/><br/>Wickers, due to testify at the coming tri=
al, doesn=E2=80=99t believe Blumhouse had a legal requirement to blur the n=
ames. And Netflix is leaning hard on First Amendment principles. =E2=80=9CI=
ndividuals, documentary filmmakers, and the press have the right to tell a =
story of public interest even when it sweeps in otherwise private informati=
on of third parties,=E2=80=9D its lawyers argue.<br/><br/>Despite arguments=
 that the inclusion of names added to the film=E2=80=99s credibility and au=
thenticity, Judge Pratt was dismissive. Then again, she hasn=E2=80=99t barr=
ed Netflix from drawing the bigger picture for jurors. With a lot of money =
on the line, I anticipate Netflix will contest the notion that it should be=
 financially penalized for a fleeting glimpse of footage that perhaps no
one paused to scrutinize. Netflix may also push a counter-narrative about t=
he need to shield speech against opportunistic litigation. A sordid and sad=
 tale of a deeply disturbed fertility doctor isn=E2=80=99t the only legacy =
these jurors will inherit. They=E2=80=99ll be grappling with the constituti=
onal DNA in our legal code that=E2=80=99s designed to safeguard free expres=
sion, too.<br/></td>
         </tr>
